1 Pascuus is used only of land and the like (as ‘pascuus ager ', ‘pascua rura ⁷, ‘pascua silva')‚ never of animals. Either, there- fore, the MS. reading ovibus pascuis is corrupt, or it involves a blunder. It is possible, but hardly probable‚ that Dante may have been misled by such passages of the Vulgate as Psalm lxxviii. 13 (‘ oves pascuae tuae ⁹) and Psalm xcix. 3 (‘0ves pascuae eius ³), where pascuae is not the adjective, but the genitive singular of pascua. It seems necessary, therefore, to supply in, which (in MS. i) might easily have been overlooked by a careless copyist. The phrase ‘ in pascuis ’ occurs in this same letter (l. 100). Giuliani recognized the difficulty and read pascui, but in mediaeval Latin the neuter pascuum was not used in the singular; the rule being that for the singular the feminine pascua should be used, and for the plural either the feminine pascuae or the neuter pascua. Thus Giovanni da Genova says in the catholicon: ‘ A pasco, -scis, derivatur hec pascua, —scue ; unde in psalmo : In loco pascue ibi me collocavit. Sed in plurali est neutri generis, scilicet, hec pascua, -orum3 unde Ezech. xxxiiii: Nonne satis erat vobis pascua bona depasci. Invenitur etiam in feminino genere hec pascue, -arwm3 unde idem propheta in eodem capitulo: Insuper et reliquias pascuarum vestrarum conculcastis pedibus vestris. Idem in eodem capitulo: In montibus excelsis Israel erunt pascue earum.'
